value.value: O'Sullivan McLeod syndrome is a benign lower motor neuron disorder and a rare variant of monomelic amyotrophy (MA), characterized by an initial unilateral weakness in the intrinsic hand muscles that eventually spreads to the opposite limb (with an asymmetrical distribution) and that has a very slow progression of muscular atrophy over a 20 year period.
Atypical teratoid rhabdoid tumor (ATRT) is a highly malignant central nervous system (CNS) rhabdoid tumor (RT) found almost exclusively in children.

Myxoid/round cell liposarcoma (MRCLS) is a type of liposarcoma (LS) mostly located in the limbs, with a variable behavior depending on the histological subtype. Both myxoid and round cell are distinct histological subtypes of LS.

Pleomorphic liposarcoma (PLS), the rarest subtype of liposarcoma (LS), is an aggressive, fast growing tumor located usually in the deep soft tissues of the lower and upper extremities. It is characterized by a variable number of pleomorphic lipoblasts and, in contrast to dedifferentiated liposarcoma, it lacks any association with well-differentiated liposarcoma.

A high-grade subtype of liposarcoma (LS) that progresses from well-differentiated liposarcoma (WDLS), and most often occurs in the retroperitoneum. It is defined as a region of nonlipogenic sarcoma associated with WDLS.

Apnea of prematurity is a developmental disorder affecting premature infants, likely secondary to an immaturity of respiratory control resulting in idiopathic pauses in breathing often associated with reduced heart rate and arterial blood oxygen levels. It may be exacerbated by concurrent neonatal diseases.

Intermediate DEND syndrome (iDEND) is a rare mild form of DEND syndrome, a neonatal diabetes mellitus, developmental delay and epilepsy condition. The intermediate form is characterized clinically by mild motor, speech or cognitive delay and an absence of epilepsy.

Complex regional pain syndrome type 2 (CRPS2), or causalgia is a form of complex regional pain syndrome that develops after damage to a peripheral nerve and is characterized by spontaneous pain, allodynia and hyperalgesia, not necessarily limited to the territory of the injured nerve, as well as at some point, edema, changes in skin blood flow or sudomotor dysfunction in the pain area.
A latent susceptibility to disease at the genetic level, which may be activated under certain conditions.

label.value: central nervous system nongerminomatous germ cell tumor

value.value: Germ cell tumors of the central nervous system other than germinoma. This category includes teratoma, choriocarcinoma, embryonal carcinoma, and yolk sac tumor.
A ventricular tachycardia that is irregular in rate and rhythm.
Inflammation of the blood vessel wall characterized by palpable purpura.
A germ cell tumor that arises from the testis or ovary and occurs during childhood.
Inflammation of the mucous membranes.
A term that refers to germinoma, seminoma, or dysgerminoma.
A tumor with perivascular epithelioid cell differentiation characterized by the absence of pleomorphism and scarcity or absence of mitotic figures.
A non-metastasizing neoplasm that arises from the uterine ligament.
Chromosomal disorder in which chromosome 17 is affected.
Any form of anemia that results from the absence of, or the defective action of, any enzyme.

label.value: anemia due to erythrocyte enzyme disorder

value.value: Any form of anemia that results from the absence of, or the defective action of, any enzyme involved in erythropoiesis.
A coagulation disorder characterized by the partial or complete absence of factor V activity in the blood.
A coagulation disorder characterized by the partial or complete absence of factor XI activity in the blood.
A lung tumor that arises from perivascular epithelioid cells (PECs).
A germ cell tumor that arises within the myocardium or cardiac chambers. The reported cases have been teratomas and yolk sac tumors.
Infection due to organisms from the genus Mycobacteria.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the pharynx. Representative examples include pharyngitis and carcinoma.

A benign hair follicle neoplasm with trichoblastic differentiation. It usually presents as a solitary papular lesion It most often presents on the head and neck area, but it may develop in any anatomic site containing hair follicles. Because of its benign nature, treatment usually is not required, provided that the diagnosis has been established with certainty.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder affecting the abducens nerve (sixth cranial nerve).
An angiokeratoma that is located on the scrotum.
A syndrome resulting from the inadequate absorption of nutrients in the small intestine. Symptoms include abdominal pain, bloating, and diarrhea.
Deficiency of a coagulation factor that is not caused by genetic alterations. Causes include vitamin K deficiency, amyloidosis, and severe liver disease.

An acute and painful inflammatory process that affects the pharynx. It is usually caused by viruses and less often bacteria. Signs and symptoms include discomfort on swallowing, low-grade fever, headache, and earache.
Viral encephalitis that is transmitted by mosquitos.
Any Simpson-Golabi-Behmel syndrome in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the GPC3 gene.
A rare genodermatosis with great phenotypic variation and characterized most commonly by ichthyosis, chondrodysplasia punctata (CDP), asymmetric shortening of the limbs, cataracts and short stature.
X-linked dominant form of disease.
X-linked recessive form of disease.
Any Liddle syndrome in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the SCNN1B gene.

value.value: A malignant meningioma with aggressive clinical course. It recurs in approximately 50-78% of the cases. This category includes the anaplastic (malignant) meningioma, papillary meningioma, and rhabdoid meningioma.
